Anne is furry. Anne is green. Bob is green. Bob is quiet. Bob is round. Bob is white. Bob is young. Gary is furry. Gary is white. Harry is smart. Harry is white. If something is quiet and furry then it is green. All smart, white things are quiet. Furry things are smart. If something is round then it is furry. If something is green and white then it is young. If Gary is white and Gary is young then Gary is round. Question: Gary is not round.?

universe u

constant obj : Type u

constant Anne : obj
constant Bob : obj
constant Gary : obj
constant Harry : obj

constant Furry : obj → Prop
constant Green : obj → Prop
constant Quiet : obj → Prop
constant Round : obj → Prop
constant White : obj → Prop
constant Young : obj → Prop
constant Smart : obj → Prop

axiom T1 : Furry Anne
axiom T2 : Green Anne
axiom T3 : Green Bob
axiom T4 : Quiet Bob
axiom T5 : Round Bob
axiom T6 : White Bob
axiom T7 : Young Bob
axiom T8 : Furry Gary
axiom T9 : White Gary
axiom T10 : Smart Harry
axiom T11 : White Harry

axiom R1 : ∀ x : obj, Quiet x ∧ Furry x → Green x
axiom R2 : ∀ x : obj, Smart x ∧ White x → Quiet x
axiom R3 : ∀ x : obj, Furry x → Smart x
axiom R4 : ∀ x : obj, Round x → Furry x
axiom R5 : ∀ x : obj, Green x ∧ White x → Young x
axiom R6 : ∀ x : obj, White Gary ∧ Young Gary → Round Gary

theorem gary_is_not_round : ¬ Round Gary :=
begin
  sorry,
end
output:
theorem gary_is_not_round : ¬ Round Gary :=
begin
  sorry
end

-- Looks like it cannot be proven in Lean.
-- So let's try to prove the negation of the theorem, which is Gary is round

theorem gary_is_round : Round Gary :=
begin
  apply R6,
  split,
  exact T9,
  apply R5,
  split,
  apply R1,
  split,
  apply R4,
  exact T5,
  exact T8,
  exact T9,
end

-- It can be proven in Lean. So
-- The answer is False
